            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Morgan Riley\u2019s world is one of scheduled stops and the steady rumble of a diesel engine. Born and raised in Vacaville, she is the daughter of a long-haul truck driver and a pharmacy technician. Her childhood was steeped in the practical realities of a working-class family; dinner table conversations were more about overtime and freight schedules than college endowments. This upbringing instilled in her a deep appreciation for the complex, unseen systems that keep society moving.\n\nInitially, Morgan pursued this interest academically, enrolling in a Logistics Management program at a state college. However, she found the theoretical coursework disconnected from the hands-on world she knew. The mounting student debt felt like an anchor. The turning point came during a visit home when her father, worn down by decades on the road, talked about the security of his union pension. A few weeks later, Morgan saw a hiring ad for Muni operators. It promised a good wage, benefits, and a tangible role in the city\u2019s circulatory system. She dropped out of college and never looked back.\n\nNow, at 27, Morgan operates the 38 Geary line, a route she knows as well as the lines on her own hands. Her life is a rhythm of early shifts and navigating the chaotic ballet of San Francisco traffic. She lives in a small apartment in the Inner Richmond, a neighborhood she loves for its foggy mornings and proximity to Golden Gate Park. Her commute is a short bus ride\u2014a chance to see her work from the other side.\n\nHer social life is a tight-knit circle of fellow operators and a few old friends. They bond over shared frustrations and triumphs in dive bars after their shifts. While she\u2019s currently single, focused on building her savings, Morgan dreams of buying a small condo, maybe just outside the city. Her aspirations aren't grand; she wants stability, to perhaps move into a training or supervisory role within the SFMTA, and to ensure her parents can have a comfortable retirement. For Morgan, being a Muni operator isn\u2019t just a job; it\u2019s an identity. She is a vital, moving part of San Francisco, a steady presence navigating the city she proudly, and complicatedly, calls home."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe was 20, home for a weekend from college. Her father, smelling of diesel and road weariness, sat at the kitchen table rubbing his back. He spoke about his union pension, not with pride, but with the relief of a man reaching a distant shore. The word \u201csecurity\u201d suddenly had a physical weight. In that moment, her student debt felt like an anchor and her logistics textbooks felt like a lie. It wasn't a choice to leave school; it was a realization of what truly mattered.\n\n2.\nAge 22. Her first solo run on the 38 Geary. Her hands were sweating on the massive steering wheel, every bump in the road a jolt to her system. When the doors hissed open at her first stop and an elderly woman smiled, a wave of profound purpose washed over her terror. She wasn\u2019t just driving; she was carrying a piece of the city. That day, the bus felt less like a machine and more like an extension of herself, a responsibility she was proud to claim.\n\n3.\nIt was a rainy Tuesday night about two years ago. A quiet older man, a regular on her late shift, was getting off at 25th Avenue. He always just nodded. But this time, he paused at the door, turned, and said, \u201cThank you, Morgan. For always being here.\u201d Hearing her name, being truly seen, felt more validating than any paycheck. It reminded her that she wasn\u2019t navigating a route, but the delicate, everyday lives of San Franciscans, and that steadiness was a form of kindness.\n\n4.\nShe was 26, sitting in a dim dive bar with three other operators after a brutal shift. Everyone was venting until Dave, a 20-year veteran, raised his beer. \u201cTo Riley,\u201d he said, \u201cfor handling that mess at Masonic without even flinching.\u201d The shared laughter and the genuine respect in his eyes felt like a formal induction. In that noisy bar, surrounded by people who just *got it*, her circle of colleagues finally, truly, felt like family. It was a shield against the city\u2019s chaos.\n\n5.\nLast fall, on a morning so foggy the world seemed to end twenty feet away, she took a walk in Golden Gate Park before her shift. The damp air smelled of eucalyptus and earth. The city\u2019s roar was a distant, muffled hum. She felt completely anonymous yet deeply rooted, a part of the quiet, breathing landscape of the Inner Richmond. It was a moment of profound peace, the kind that reminded her why she chose to stay in this complicated, beautiful place that she now called home."
